🌐 Easy Explanation of the IPv4 Receive Path (But Complete)
==========================================================

When an IPv4 packet arrives at your machine, the Linux kernel follows a very
specific path to process it. The diagram you posted shows that flow.

Let’s break it down from start to finish.

1️⃣ Packet Arrives at Network Driver
------------------------------------
- Your network card receives an Ethernet frame.
- The Ethernet driver hands this packet to the Linux network stack.
- Linux sees the Ethernet type 0x0800 → means the payload is IPv4.
- Earlier during boot, Linux already registered the IPv4 handler (ip_rcv()),
  so the packet is passed to ip_rcv().

2️⃣ ip_rcv() — First Checkpoint (Sanity Checks)
-----------------------------------------------
ip_rcv() is the main entry point for all IPv4 packets (unicast, multicast, broadcast).

Inside ip_rcv():

✔️ Header Length Check
   - IPv4 header has a variable length (ihl in units of 4 bytes).
   - Minimum valid header = 20 bytes.
   - So ihl must be ≥ 5.
   - If less → packet is corrupt → drop.

✔️ Version Check
   - IPv4 version must be 4.
   - If not 4 → drop.

✔️ Checksum Check
   - RFC 1122 requires every host to verify the IPv4 header checksum.
   - Kernel calls ip_fast_csum().
   - If checksum is bad → packet is silently dropped.

If all checks are OK → next step.
3️⃣ Netfilter Hook: NF_INET_PRE_ROUTING
---------------------------------------
After sanity checks, ip_rcv() calls:

   NF_HOOK(NFPROTO_IPV4, NF_INET_PRE_ROUTING, skb, dev, NULL, ip_rcv_finish)

This is the first interception point for Netfilter/iptables.

At this stage, Netfilter modules can:

   ACCEPT → continue normal processing.
   DROP   → discard packet immediately.
   STOLEN → Netfilter takes ownership; IPv4 stack stops further handling.
   QUEUE / REPEAT / STOP → advanced behaviors.

If no Netfilter rules or everything ACCEPTs → processing continues
to ip_rcv_finish().


4️⃣ ip_rcv_finish() — Routing Decision
--------------------------------------
This is where the real IPv4 logic begins.

The routing decision happens **inside ip_rcv_finish()**, specifically during
the routing lookup:

   ip_route_input_noref(skb, iph->daddr, iph->saddr, iph->tos, skb->dev);

This function:

   - Checks routing tables
   - Determines if the destination IP belongs to:
        • local host
        • another machine (forwarding)
        • multicast
   - Builds the dst entry
   - Sets the callback that will run next:

        dst->input = ip_local_deliver   // packet for this machine
        dst->input = ip_forward         // packet must be forwarded
        dst->input = ip_mr_input        // multicast case

ip_rcv_finish() then executes:

   dst_input(skb);

dst_input() simply calls the function chosen earlier:

   skb->dst->input(skb);


5️⃣ Case 1: Local Delivery Path
-------------------------------
If routing says the packet belongs to the local machine:

Step A → ip_local_deliver()
   - Prepares the packet for transport-layer processing.

Netfilter Hook: NF_INET_LOCAL_IN
   - Second interception point.
   - Local firewall rules can drop or modify packets.

Step B → ip_local_deliver_finish()
   - Decodes the Protocol field.
   - Passes the packet to the correct transport layer:

        TCP  → tcp_v4_rcv()
        UDP  → udp_rcv()
        ICMP → icmp_rcv()

This completes the local delivery path.


6️⃣ Case 2: Forwarding Path (Linux acting as a Router)
------------------------------------------------------
If routing says the packet must be forwarded:

Step A → ip_forward()
   - Decreases TTL
   - Recalculates header checksum
   - Applies forwarding rules

Netfilter Hook: NF_INET_FORWARD
   - Third interception point for forwarded traffic.

Step B → ip_forward_finish()
   - Prepares the packet for sending to the next hop.

Packet then goes to the Tx (Transmit) path (ip_output(), etc.)

